SIMPLE: groove
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Groove
<hw>Groove</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[D. <ets>groef</ets>,
<ets>groeve</ets>; akin to E. <ets>grove</ets>. See
<er>Grove</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A furrow, channel, or long
hollow, such as may be formed by cutting, molding, grinding, the wearing
force of flowing water, or constant travel; a depressed way; a worn
path; a rut.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence: The habitual course of life, work, or
affairs; fixed routine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The gregarious trifling of life in the social
<qex>groove</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>J. Morley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <ety>[See <er>Grove</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mining)</fld>
<def>A shaft or excavation.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Groove</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Groove
<hw>Groove</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Grooved</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Groving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To cut a groove or channel in; to
form into channels or grooves; to furrow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>grooved</ent>⟦br⟧
